      <data key="d8">EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d9">APPLIED_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">The evaluated isolation room is located in an emergency department, so the findings are directly applicable to emergency care settings that manage airborne infectious patients.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="DISTANCE FROM THE CONTAMINANT SOURCE" target="INFECTION RISK">
      <data key="d7">DISTANCE FROM THE CONTAMINANT SOURCE</data>
      <data key="d8">INFECTION RISK</data>
      <data key="d9">REDUCES</data>
      <data key="d10">Increasing distance from the contaminant source (patient) generally reduces infection risk in transient coughing situations, with a stronger effect at higher flow rates.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="TRANSIENT COUGHING SITUATION" target="INFECTION RISK">
      <data key="d7">TRANSIENT COUGHING SITUATION</data>
      <data key="d8">INFECTION RISK</data>
      <data key="d9">TARGETS</data>
      <data key="d10">The transient coughing scenario is used as the exposure condition under which changes in infection risk with distance and ventilation are evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="NEGATIVE-PRESSURIZED ISOLATION ROOM" target="EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS">
      <data key="d7">NEGATIVE-PRESSURIZED ISOLATION ROOM</data>
      <data key="d8">EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d9">APPLIED_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">The negative-pressurized isolation room is implemented within the emergency department setting, making the emergency department the operational context for this specialized hospital zone.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION PERFORMANCE" target="NEGATIVE-PRESSURIZED ISOLATION ROOM">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION PERFORMANCE</data>
      <data key="d8">NEGATIVE-PRESSURIZED ISOLATION ROOM</data>
      <data key="d9">APPLIED_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Ventilation performance metrics are evaluated specifically for the negative-pressurized isolation room to determine how effectively this room controls airborne contaminants.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION PERFORMANCE" target="VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION PERFORMANCE</data>
      <data key="d8">VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d9">COMPLEMENTS</data>
      <data key="d10">Ventilation performance metrics are used to compare and optimize different ventilation configurations, linking measured effectiveness to specific design choices.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS" target="HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM</data>
      <data key="d9">APPLIED_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Alternative ventilation configurations are deployed in the hospital isolation room to modify airflow patterns and influence droplet transport.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION" target="COUGH DROPLETS">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">COUGH DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d9">REDUCES</data>
      <data key="d10">Appropriate ventilation can reduce the concentration and residence time of cough droplets in indoor air by diluting and removing them through airflow and exhaust.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">REDUCES</data>
      <data key="d10">By diluting and removing virus-laden droplets and aerosols, ventilation can reduce airborne concentrations of SARS-CoV-2 in indoor environments.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION" target="AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d9">REDUCES</data>
      <data key="d10">Ventilation reduces the concentration of infectious aerosols in indoor air by diluting them with outdoor or filtered air and exhausting contaminated air, thereby lowering occupants’ airborne exposure dose and associated infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION" target="CARBON DIOXIDE">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">CARBON DIOXIDE</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DOSE</data>
      <data key="d10">Ventilation performance is operationally characterized by indoor carbon dioxide levels, where the effective dose or rate of ventilation is inferred from the resulting steady-state CO₂ concentration relative to outdoor levels.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION" target="HUMANS">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">HUMANS</data>
      <data key="d9">APPLIED_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Ventilation is applied to indoor environments occupied by humans to control the buildup of exhaled carbon dioxide and respiratory aerosols, thereby improving indoor air quality and reducing airborne exposure for occupants.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS" target="HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM">
      <data key="d7">BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM</data>
      <data key="d9">APPLIED_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">The study examines cough droplet behavior within a hospital isolation room, using this room type as the physical context for airflow and droplet dispersion analysis.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS" target="VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS">
      <data key="d7">BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d9">APPLIED_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">The study compares different ventilation configurations implemented in the isolation room to determine their impact on cough droplet transport and removal.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS" target="COUGH DROPLETS">
      <data key="d7">BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">COUGH DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d9">TARGETS</data>
      <data key="d10">The primary focus of the study is the behavior of cough droplets, including their trajectories, deposition, and residence time under different ventilation setups.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">TARGETS</data>
      <data key="d10">By modeling cough droplets emitted from a COVID-19 case, the study indirectly targets the airborne transport of SARS-CoV-2 carried by those droplets.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="SUMMARY OF HUMAN RESPONSES TO VENTILATION" target="VENTILATION">
      <data key="d7">SUMMARY OF HUMAN RESPONSES TO VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The review compiles evidence on how different ventilation rates and patterns affect human comfort, symptoms, and performance, supporting the role of ventilation as a key indoor environmental control.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.6</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
